    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Wide-screen process created by Fred Waller and used commercially beginning in 1952. The system employed a vast curved screen with three overlapping 35mm projectors each in a separate booth, with one on the right projecting onto the left third of the screen, the one in the center pointed straight ahead, and the one on the left projecting onto the right third of the screen. Most productions were travelogues, and "How the West Was Won "(1962) was one of the few fiction films produced in Cinerama.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000047993/Konigsberg, The Complete Film Dictionary (1987)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Breedbeeldprocedé dat werd ontwikkeld door Fred Waller en sinds 1952 commercieel wordt gebruikt. Het systeem gebruikt een groot gebogen scherm met drie overlappende 35mm-projectoren, elk in een aparte cabine. De camera rechts projecteert op het linker derde deel van het scherm, de camera in het midden is recht vooruit gericht en de camera links projecteert op het rechter derde deel van het scherm. De meeste producties waren reisfilms; 'How the West Was Won' (1962) was een van de weinige fictiefilms die werden gefilmd in Cinerama.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Processo de tela larga criado por Fred Waller e usado comercialmente a partir de 1952. O sistema empregava uma vasta tela curva com três projetores de 35 mm sobrepostos cada um em uma cabine separada, com um à direita projetando-se no terço esquerdo da tela, o outro em o centro apontava diretamente para a frente e o da esquerda projetando-se no terço direito da tela. </Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Portuguese</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000316/CVAA-BR</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
